Additional Tips

Full System Scan: Use autorunsc.exe -a * -c -h (from Sysinternals) to export all autoruns to CSV for review.
Event Logs: Check for creations via wevtutil qe Microsoft-Windows-Sysmon/Operational /q:"*[System/EventID=13]" (if Sysmon installed) for registry changes.
PowerShell Module: Install and run Get-PSAutorun from PSGallery for a one-stop check: Install-Module -Name PSAutoRun; Get-PSAutorun.
Monitoring: Use Procmon (Sysinternals) with filters for registry writes: Run procmon.exe, set filter to "Operation is RegSetValue".
This isn't exhaustive (Windows has hundreds of ASEPs), but covers 90%+ of real-world cases. For removal, delete suspicious entries carefully—backup first with reg export HKLM backup.reg. If unsure, consult a professional.





Why Get-CimInstance Matters for Persistence Detection

Many attackers prefer WMI subscriptions over registry Run keys because they're harder to spot with basic tools.
Get-CimInstance lets you directly query the WMI repository (especially the root\subscription namespace) to find suspicious __EventFilter, __EventConsumer, and __FilterToConsumerBinding objects.
It is the preferred way over Get-WmiObject (which is deprecated in newer PowerShell versions).

Key Commands to Hunt WMI Persistence with Get-CimInstance
Run these in an elevated PowerShell prompt. They focus on the subscription namespace where persistence lives.

List all Event Filters (the trigger conditions)PowerShellGet-CimInstance -Namespace root\subscription -ClassName __EventFilter
Look for suspicious Name, Query, or EventNamespace values (e.g., anything referencing unusual processes, logons, or file paths).

List all Event Consumers (the payload/action that runs)PowerShellGet-CimInstance -Namespace root\subscription -ClassName __EventConsumer
This returns generic objects. Pipe to see concrete types:PowerShellGet-CimInstance -Namespace root\subscription -ClassName __EventConsumer | Select-Object __CLASS, Name, @{Name="Command";Expression={$_.CommandLineTemplate}}, @{Name="Script";Expression={$_.ScriptText}}
Suspicious types include:
CommandLineEventConsumer → runs cmd.exe, powershell.exe, etc.
ActiveScriptEventConsumer → runs VBS/JScript
ScriptingEventConsumer variants

Specific consumer classes (more readable):PowerShellGet-CimInstance -Namespace root\subscription -ClassName CommandLineEventConsumer
Get-CimInstance -Namespace root\subscription -ClassName ActiveScriptEventConsumer
List Bindings (connects filter to consumer — this is what actually activates persistence)PowerShellGet-CimInstance -Namespace root\subscription -ClassName __FilterToConsumerBinding
Critical: If you see a binding between a suspicious filter and a suspicious consumer, that's active persistence.

One-liner to show the full picture (most useful)PowerShellGet-CimInstance -Namespace root\subscription -ClassName __EventFilter |
    ForEach-Object {
        $filter = $_
        $$   binding = Get-CimInstance -Namespace root\subscription -ClassName __FilterToConsumerBinding -Filter "Filter = ""   $$($filter.__PATH)"""
        if ($binding) {
            $consumer = Get-CimInstance -Namespace root\subscription -Query "SELECT * FROM $($$   binding.Consumer.Split('=')[1].TrimStart('"').TrimEnd('"')) WHERE __PATH = '   $$($binding.Consumer)'"
            [PSCustomObject]@{
                FilterName   = $filter.Name
                Query        = $filter.Query
                ConsumerName = $consumer.Name
                ConsumerType = $consumer.__CLASS
                Command      = if ($consumer.__CLASS -eq 'CommandLineEventConsumer') { $consumer.CommandLineTemplate }
                               elseif ($consumer.__CLASS -eq 'ActiveScriptEventConsumer') { $consumer.ScriptText }
            }
        }
    } | Format-Table -AutoSize
Quick suspicious filter search (common malicious patterns)PowerShellGet-CimInstance -Namespace root\subscription -ClassName __EventFilter | Where-Object { $_.Query -match "SELECT|__InstanceCreationEvent|Win32_Process" -or $_.Name -notmatch "^Microsoft|Windows" }

Other Useful Get-CimInstance Queries for Persistence Hunting
While not directly for WMI subscriptions, these help spot related artifacts:

Running processes (malware might show up here):PowerShellGet-CimInstance Win32_Process | Select Name, CommandLine, ProcessId | Sort Name
Installed services (some persistence uses services):PowerShellGet-CimInstance Win32_Service | Where-Object { $_.StartMode -eq "Auto" } | Select Name, PathName, State
Autorun-like registry keys via WMI (less common, but possible):PowerShellInvoke-CimMethod -Namespace root\default -ClassName StdRegProv -MethodName GetStringValue -Arguments @{hDefKey=2147483650; sSubKeyName="SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run"; sValueName="SomeKey"}

Comparison: Get-CimInstance vs Older Methods

Get-WmiObject → works, but deprecated; use Get-CimInstance instead.
wmic → still works: wmic /NAMESPACE:\\root\subscription PATH __EventFilter GET /FORMAT:LIST
Autoruns (Sysinternals) → has a dedicated WMI tab that shows these subscriptions graphically — often the easiest way to spot and delete them.


